                        <incipit>
                           <locus from="1r">Fol. 1<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>.</locus>
                           Gloriosissimo regi ceolwlfo Beda famulo christi.
                        </incipit>
                        
                        <explicit>
                           <locus from="1v">Fol. 1<hi rend="superscript">v</hi>.</locus>
                           posteritas lateris mandare studi minus. 
                          </explicit>
                        
                        <incipit>
                           Posteritas occeani insula quondam albion nomen fuit. 
                        </incipit>
                        
                        <explicit>
                           <locus from="101vb">Fol. 101<hi rend="superscript">vb</hi>.</locus>
                           peruenire. et parere semper ante faciem tuam. Preterea omnes ad quos hac eadem historia peruenire potuerit
                        </explicit>
                        
                        <explicit>
                           <locus from="102">Fol. 102<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>.</locus>
                           intercessionis inueniam. Amen.
                        </explicit>
                        <note>[Capitula follow, fols. Fol. 102<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>-105<hi rend="superscript">r</hi></note>
                        
                        <author key="person_61539765">Bede</author>
                        
                        <title key="work_968">Historia ecclesiastica gentis anglorum</title>
                        
                        <listBibl>
                           <bibl>Ed. B. Colgrave and R. A. B. Mynors (Oxford, 1969).</bibl>
                        </listBibl>
                        <note>(This manuscript listed p. lvi, among copies of <q>the common text of Southern England in the later Middle Ages</q>). In other manuscripts <q>Preterea omnes inueniam</q> (edn. 6) is found at the end of the preface.</note>
                        
                     </msItem>
                     
                     <msItem n="2" xml:id="All_Souls_College_MS_31-part1-item2">
                        <incipit>
                           <locus from="105v">Fol. 105<hi rend="superscript">v</hi>.</locus>
                           Cornelius nepos salustio crispo suo salutem... ad pollicitum reuertamur. Pelias rex in penelaponense esonem fratrem habuit.</incipit>
                        
                        <explicit>
                           <locus from="115rb/2">Fol. 115<hi rend="superscript">rb</hi>/2.</locus>
                           Antenorem secuti duo milia quingenti helenum mine ducenti. Quis troianorum quem grecorum occiderunt... Diomedes. antyppum [<hi rend="italic">sic</hi>]. Mestem [<hi rend="italic">sic</hi>]. 
                        </explicit>
                        
                        <finalRubric>
                           Explicit vastacio. Troie.
                        </finalRubric>
                        
                        <author key="person_55518848">Dares Phrygius</author>
                        <title key="work_16459">De excidio troiae</title>
                        
                        <listBibl>
                           <bibl>Ed. F. Meister (Leipzig, 1873).</bibl>
                        </listBibl>
                       
                        <note><q>Quis troianorum</q> is the beginning of the usual two supplementary sections, nineteen lines in all, for which see <bibl><hi rend="italic">CR</hi> i. 12-13.</bibl>
                        </note>
                        
                     </msItem>
                     <msItem n="3" xml:id="All_Souls_College_MS_31-part1-item3">
                   
                        <incipit>
                           <locus from="115v">Fol. 115<hi rend="superscript">v</hi>.</locus>
                           Britannia qui beatissima est insularum fecunda frugibus
                        </incipit>
                        <explicit>
                           <locus from="199r">Fol. 199<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>.</locus>
                           adnichillata est
                        </explicit>
                        
                        <incipit>
                           Hic est annus
                        </incipit>
                        <incipit>
                           <locus from="200ra">Fol. 200<hi rend="superscript">ra</hi>.</locus> 
                           vt aqua in vase terebrato defluit et nil habens.
                        </incipit>
                    
                        <finalRubric>Hec sunt nomina regum christianorum in anglia.</finalRubric>
                       
                        <explicit>Rex primus fuit Hine</explicit>
                        
                        <explicit>
                           <locus from="200v">Fol. 200<hi rend="superscript">v</hi>.</locus> 
                           migrauit ad dominum die sancti edmundi archiepiscopi et sepultus est die sancti eadmundi regis et martinis in ecclesia beati petri apud Westmonasterium.
                        </explicit>
                        
                        <author key="person_57425612">Henry of Huntingdon</author>
                        <title key="work_2003">Historia Anglorum</title>
                        
                        <listBibl>
                           <bibl>Ed. D. E. Greenway, <title rend="italic">Henry, Archdeacon of Huntingdon, Historia Anglorum</title> (Oxford, 1996).</bibl> 
                        </listBibl>
                        <note>
                           Our manuscript, Greenway's MS (O), is derived from a lost copy of Aberystwyth, National Library of Wales, <idno type="shelfmark">Peniarth 382 (Hengwrt 101)</idno>, in which the text is in seven books and ends at 1129 (edn. 252/4). 
                           For a brief description of our manuscript see her p. cxxxvii. 
                           On the confused dating of the epilogue, beginning <q>Hic est annus</q> and continuing <q>qui comprehendit scriptorem annum tricesimo regni... regis Anglorum henrici annus lx. ab aduentu normannorum... annus gracie m<hi rend="superscript">us</hi> c<hi rend="superscript">us</hi> 1.xiiij<hi rend="superscript">us</hi> [sic]... </q>, see edn. xlii n. 1.
                        </note>
                     </msItem>
                     
